Let's say this is about Higgs' boson, because the chances of making mistakes seem minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is, in this world, one law that is absolutely inevitable, saying that two things can't end up in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to get past this rule, don't even try too hard, otherwise you'll hurt yourself.
But while physics of elementary particles is a rather strange world, it turns out that there's one law of this kind in it too: Paulie's exclusion principle, which suggests that two particles cannot take the same space at the same point in time, if they're in the same "quantum state" -- this "state" is, in general, some of their characteristics.
So physics divides particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens, called farmers, who wisely follow the principle of Paulie.
The other is the fuss of a boson, an abominable gang of anarchists, who have no respect for anything, at least for this principle, which means that they can calmly find themselves in the same place at the same time.
