These very bosons, it should be stressed, are not all such exotic creatures as might be thought of.
In fact, if you can read this chronology, it's because of one incredibly banal boson, a photon, or "part of the light," which is the "courier" of an electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a single particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "breaks" an electromagnetic field in this particular place, about as a rock thrown into the pond.
This "violation" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) and it is nothing but a photon, and hence one of the "power carrier" bosons.
A more stable field
The same thing happens with Higgs' boson, with the only difference that in order for that boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "broken."
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; in order to energize it, it must be achieved with very high and very high energy, as if it were a frozen pond whose surface could only shake a very large stone.
