Effect
It is harder to predict from these studies for the daily lives of average humans, but it would be a mistake to assume that they are not.
See, in the early 1960s, the laser pioneers in Bella's labs couldn't even imagine what revolution their work would trigger.
They anticipated their applications in science, but nothing more.
Indeed, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who was working at Belle's Labs, where a laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (previously impulsive) in 1962, said that the laser was originally treated as a more "labular gadget".
