To pay and sell without the help of the banks--with Bitcoin
Total contrast to current monetary exchange based on central banks numbered transactions between receiving parties with commission fees for processing them.
Moreover, as often happens to these technologies, a political vision is evident: the belief that the current monetary system, composed of banking monopolies, is causing financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Sathoshi Nacomoto (pseudonom), is simultaneously a virtual currency (but convertible to dollars, Euro ...) and a protected BitTorrent type exchange protocol that allows for the exchange of files between members of the same level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been registered with 15,000 computers online.
Several thousand websites take bitcoins for donation or payment.
After reaching a maximum of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, the rate dropped to 2 dollars five months later before returning to about ten dollars today (curses are listed on Bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the world's exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its October Virtual Currency Report was interested in the system.
He describes Bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency," "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "like the usual currency."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency, like “lending” used to advance in a video game that is earned during the game or that can be bought (and sometimes traded).
The Facebook social network has also developed such a system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all network nodes are both account holders, accountants, currency issuers, purchasers and salesmen.
How does this network work?
