The Spanishissé, a small-sighted sleeping-town under the city of Rutterdam, owns an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this unfortunate circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to build seven fictitious bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of painted miniatures of iron beton.
The success of this educational initiative has been modest.
And then the city's fathers realized that they had the only way to beat the statistics: build a library here!
Vini Maas, a master of bold column charts and author of witty, sometimes even cynical structures, took up the challenge with his usual complacency and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under the mouse and a grin on his face.
