Sabo: "The Germans must play a more important role."
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Sabo, the US-European liaison expert, in doing so, is balancing the narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week Germany first indicated that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin refrained from voting.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany must now be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that the United States position is not supported either.
Germany wanted to show its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the insurgency in Libya in March 2011, Germany also refrained from voting to establish a no-fly zone.
As a result, the offer was made by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, that is, moving from the policy that the US was, to the German foreign policy itself.
The situation is compounded by the fact that Europeans do not have a coordinated single policy.
So the Germans are getting back between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not accustomed to it.
I think they're just finding out what they're doing, but they're on their way to a more normal foreign policy.
A foreign policy like that of France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It is a willingness to take a national stand independent of the position of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, export and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are very different from those of other major States, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Have these economic interests affected the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the United Nations?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
It therefore needed to be careful not to insult the public and elite in the Arab countries.
Anyway, it plays a role.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to it; it's not entirely one-sided.
But in any case, it plays an important role in German calculations.
Has Germany damaged its relationship with the US by refraining from making important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I am sure that in Europe, and even in the US, there is a prevailing understanding of the German position.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan question.
Germany might even thus gain some respect.
That signaled that it should be taken seriously as a player on the international scene and that its interests should be taken into account.
Europe has different views on the Palestinian initiative.
On the contrary, the US has made clear its support for the veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the US and many European States?
Because of American domestic policies, such differences have always existed.
I believe that Obama's government, deep down, has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But, of course, because of the local political situation, the government cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that considerable differences of opinion are not as significant as ever.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all excited about Netanyahu's politics.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the EU's most important partner on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, Germans would have been a little easier if there were a single, uncontroversial European policy, but that's not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and must instead act on the basis of their own vision.
That's what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in shaping a common European position.
It is clear that this is difficult for Germany, at least because of its connections to Israel.
This has always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they have to play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, won't it really take the lead?
Or does Germany still have a hard lead role to play?
Germany is not accustomed to this; it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, always hard to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis -- every time Germany takes on an important role, a wide range of anti-German feelings emerge.
The Germans don't just deal with it.
In fact, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must take into account a wide range of neighbours and opinions, which is not easy.
So the US's influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at present the EU is not filling this vacuum, so who is left?
The Germans will just have to play a larger role.
Even if you don't like it, it makes you uncomfortable or unloved, that's life!
Stephen Sabo is the vice-director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., where academics and political experts from Europe and North America are working together to explore the problems of the Transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the German Marshall Foundation, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and trans-Atlantic ties.
