Mariana's mother tells this story, and the portrait of her daughter looks at us from the wall, where he hangs next to the crucifixion on which only one word is written: justice.
This is what they said the family was denied.
"The state's officials treated me like an old gossiper, dissatisfied with a calmer.
They want people to just believe everything they say and keep quiet.
But it's wrong, it can't, especially when there's so many abuses and shortcomings around you," she says.
After wearing a Presidential bandage on Saturday, President Peña Nieto will take on a difficult responsibility with her.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crimes, and the new President has promised to make this a priority during his reign.
"I hope he'll be exactly the same president as the governor," says Olvera, a Congressman from Valle de Bravo from the PRI party.
But that is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Ness are most afraid of.
Bradley Manning didn't complain of any ill-treatment, claims the prosecution.
The prosecution is trying to deny Bradley Manning's claims of poor conditions of detention.
During the hearing, emphasis was placed on Manning's stay in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence demands that the case be dismissed on the ground that Manning's conditions of detention were cruel.
The U.S. military is accused of stealing several thousand secret documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in United States history, had not availed himself of many opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment which he said he had had to endure while in military prison.
During the cross-examined pre-trial hearing in Fort Mid, Maryland, the military prosecutor, Major Ashden Feyn, stated that the records of the weekly visits to Manning by the prison authorities during the nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not contain complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-trial of the defence motion to discontinue the Manning case, on the ground that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment, was carried out the day after Manning stated that he intended to commit suicide while in detention.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 was accused of stealing several thousand secret documents during his service in Iraq.
These materials were later published on the WikiLeaks web site.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During the hearing on Friday, the prosecutor, Feyn, along with Manning, examined the reports which had been completed following Manning's visits to the administration during his stay in Quantico prison, where he was held under strict prison conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
During visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When D.A. Feyn asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he considered the prison administration to be "excellent" and the general conditions of detention to be "very professionally organized".
The reports examined do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manning was directly asked about the conditions of his detention, Phein claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed his verbal concern about these issues and that the officials who visited him had discussed these issues with him and had stated that they would take care of them but had not recorded them in writing.
"They wrote "no problems" (after my complaints were discussed), but that doesn't mean I didn't raise the subject in the conversation," says Manning.
The military judge, Colonel Deniz Lindh, also asked Manning why he had not complained of the abuse of him in January 2011 during a meeting of a commission considering the suicide intentions he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to be removed from the “injury warning” regime and to ease the conditions of detention.
The military authorities explained that the restricted regime of detention, at a level lower than that of surveillance to prevent suicide, had been introduced to protect the prisoner and to protect the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm okay with them to undo the accident prevention regime... so that my standard of living would improve, in my view," explained Manning.
On Thursday, Manning witnessed his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to a prison at a navy base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thought about suicide in Kuwait and that he had once lost consciousness due to the heat.
He explained that it is psychologically difficult when you are prevented from knowing how your fate is handled and what happens in the outside world.
"My world leaned down to Camp Arifian's base, to the size of my prison," said Manning on Thursday.
- I thought I was going to die in this cell."
While in Quantico, he said that Manning spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day -- alone.
Manning reports that he was allowed to keep only mattresses, blankets, slaps, some clothes and glasses.
He says he was trying to move because sleeping or even lying down during the daytime prohibited the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, he was constantly hit by a light coming through the outside of the cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he was turning around in bed at night, he said he was waken and forced to turn around on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal objection to the abuse of Manning in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
Moreover, on Friday, the judge asked Manning about the statement he had made during his statement on Thursday that, after being forced to sleep naked one night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other prisoners during the morning check.
Manning said he couldn't cover himself with a blanket during the check.
In reply to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said that he understood from the guard's order that he should throw a blanket to cover for, but admitted that no one had directly ordered him to dump him.
On Thursday, Manning announced that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reported that he told the officer that he could use a slippery rubber or a slab to hurt himself, but he didn't do it.
That night, according to Manning's statement, his underwear, his slaps and glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account what he had to endure during his detention and would significantly reduce the sentence if Manning were found guilty by a military court which was due to start his trial early next year.
The defence stated that it intended to invite Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes and to challenge other charges as excessive.
The reopening of the hearing is scheduled this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held in Quantico in accordance with the rules regulating the detention of arrested persons under the strictest conditions.
The charges brought against Manning included aiding the enemy, illegal promotion of data on the Internet, transmission of information concerning national defence and theft of State property or documents.
If convicted of all counts, he may be sentenced to life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of an American of Mexican descent.
According to the author, many Mexicans had been forced to leave Mexico because of a lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans are inclined to blame those who have left because they remind the inhabitants of difficult times.
Reuben Navarette believes that Mexicans of American descent are breaking up between two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked through the incoming corridor, approached the border control zone and frozen on the ground.
The labels showed two queues: one for Mexicanos, one for Extremjeros.
I stood in front of them for a few seconds without knowing where to go.
I grew up in Central California, and they've always called me Mexican.
It's just a conditional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends in New York think they're Italian.
Later, I focused on the complex design of "American Mexican."
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's home, there was no need for conditional names or complex designs.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than my tongue, and I can't get rid of the American accent.
So I pulled out my American passport and was in line for Extremjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago, when the newly elected President of Mexico, Henrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The issues of migration, drugs and trade that were common to the Presidents of those countries were on the agenda.
President Peña Nieto spoke eagerly of the recovery of the Mexican economy, which would make it possible for Mexicans to stay in Mexico now, rather than to move to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the US and Canada and to create some sort of North American trade bloc like the European Union.
Moreover, President Peña Nieto had promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific suggestions had been made.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is a grave, old-fashioned matter.
Most Americans never thought that the United States had invaded Mexico in 1848 and that its leaders had been forced to abandon half their territory at gunpoint.
But Mexicans have been thinking for centuries, not for minutes, and they have seen reminders of those events in everything.
So it's only when a U.S. government actor speaks a word of criticism against Mexico, the press, and the elite of Mexican society immediately complains that Americans violate the sovereignty of their neighbours.
And the descendants of Montezuma are filled with war.
The most difficult, however, are Mexico's relations with over 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Do you want to talk about grievances?
That's enough.
There are winners and losers in Mexico, people who find opportunities in this country, and those who don't.
In L.A., L.C., L.C., Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, so many people of Mexican descent have only one reason: at some point in their family history, someone -- father or grandfather -- was unable to realize themselves in Mexico and had to go north.
Most commonly, they were Mexicans of a certain type -- dark, uneducated, poor peasant families.
We're their descendants, and we remember that.
That's not what they see in Mexico.
Today, our lives are the embodiment of an American dream, and we've been in good schools and we've got good jobs, but we can't forget that even that dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and uncertain, but we know which country to consider to be its own.
United States of America.
Besides, we know that most of the Mexican elite and rulers don't like us.
We say the same to them.
They see us as a reminder of humiliation, and they treat us as second-class people, as untrue Mexicans.
We speak not enough Spanish, and our ties to Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is due to failure.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We wouldn't be behind the silk curtain now, finding a healthy life in the United States, but losing our spiritual connections.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States when she was a child, and this reminds me that there is a certain friction between real Mexicans and Americans of Mexican origin, and Mexicans understand their national identity better, and Mexicans are hurt.
She's a U.S. citizen, and she thinks she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintances, of Mexican descent, do not feel belonging to any of them.
We're listening to a Mexican band called Los Tigers del Norte, but we love Bruce Springsteen too.
By getting the best of the two worlds, you're bound to lose your roots.
We're Americans in Mexico.
And in the United States, they call us Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relationship was already not complicated enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore their relationship with the Diaspora.
They want Americans of Mexican descent to work as Mexican ambassadors and represent their interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends what a beautiful country it is and how wonderful it is to visit it, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
It's not going to work.
Too much resentment in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country to be so beautiful.
Sorry, but take care of it yourself, amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans are still unable to forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican Americans are still offended by the way their relatives have been treated most recently in Mexico.
Yeah.
I think we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
A cease-fire agreement between Israel and the Hamas faction can become a fragile foundation for further peace
Is lasting peace possible between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodguilt leads to the conclusion that such hopes are vain.
It was a familiar, pointless debate about who had begun; numerous buildings had been turned into ruins; over 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis had been killed; and rockets fired from the Gaza Strip had dropped in the vicinity of the capital of Israel, Tel-Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem for the first time during the conflict.
However, despite the hopeless link between Israelis and the Palestinian people in their perennial conflict, the Middle East has changed.
This may be treated differently, but the events of the Arab Spring have swirled in a rioting storm with many established realityes, and the Palestinian and Israelis have not been able to stay away from the whirlwind that has shaken the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
There are, however, reasons for hope of breaking this deadly dead end.
A War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation did not give rise to a cause for optimism.
Even if the cease-fire, which was signed on 21 November, is being implemented, the fighting this week has only reinforced the positions of the protagonists on both sides.
The leaders of the Israeli Islamist movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will claim to have forced Israel to retreat despite its loss.
Despite the fact that some leaders of the faction have been destroyed and 1.7 million people have been blocked in one of the most populous and troubled parts of the world, Israel has not been able to destroy Hamas.
In fact, it is growing popularity in the West Bank of the Jordan River, another Palestinian Territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, the leaders of Hamas may well conclude that time works for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements grows in the Arab world, new powerful and rich friends have emerged.
The renaissance of the Turkish regional leader, who once was Israel's closest ally among the Islamic countries, had given support to the United Kingdom, followed by the example of Qatar, one of the richest and dynamic States in the Persian Gulf.
The glorified supporter of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland announced the creation of an Israeli-based Islamist half-month, from Lebanon to the north, which was ruled by the military Hezbollah, to Syria, where the ever-growing Islamist rebels were about to overthrow the power of Bashar Assad, and further to Jordan, where the King's authorities threatened the allies of the United Kingdom.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country in Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood was enhanced under President Muhammad Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who had ruled Egypt for 30 years and had been overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to the support of Hamas.
The Muslims, on the contrary, are a much-like organization, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic positions, Hamas can become a significant player whose voice will not be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, the hardline in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli anti-ballistic missile system, the "Iron dome" system, had justified the cost of its creation and had successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
Israelis can sleep quietly, at least for a while.
In the area of diplomacy, the US has remained firm; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for launching the last round of violence.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, particularly under the Government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that some 30 Israelis had died since 2004 from rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel had managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, partly at the expense of the wall which entered the West Bank of the Jordan, a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian State, and protected Jewish settlements, which continued to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party, in preparation for the elections to be held on 22 January, has merged with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Liberiaman, is very convenient.
What's the point of persuading the Palestinian people and giving them their own State?
If they hand over all the power in the West Bank, would they not start launching rockets from there towards Israel, as their companions in the Gaza Strip did?
It's best to keep them outside the wall and severely suppress any attempt to lift their heads.
It is possible that hard-line advocates will win; however, their calculations may be denied in the Arabic spring.
While Islamists, who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere, do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defensive part of Israel's budget is larger than all its Arab neighbours combined.
Launching a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments to strengthen their own economy.
The pragmatism of the President of Egypt, Mursi, who worked with Barack Obama to stop the fire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel must, to no lesser extent, bear in mind the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic changes have taken place in the Arab countries, depriving the Palestinian people of their right to self-determination is a time bomb that will explode sooner or later in the occupied Israeli territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel-Aviv this week.
The repression already undermines the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish State, and the demographic aspect -- the growth of the Arab population -- only makes those problems worse.
The bloodthirsty operations carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to be paid for by the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need external momentum
There remains the only solution to which sane representatives on both sides are constantly calling for, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two States and Israel's transfer of lands in exchange for security.
The hope remains, not too strong in the short term, that a cease-fire will enable other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, long overdue in its decision to stop arms flows to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, has a more favourable position than ever in order to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish State since 1967, taking into account the exchange of lands and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries must also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
That would do more to create a Palestinian State than the upcoming vote in the United Nations, which could result in a recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama has a role to play in bringing Israel to the table.
During his first term, he had not submitted his own peace plan.
Upon his return to the White House, he remained reluctant to join the problem.
This is a devastating short-sighted position.
The United States is vitally interested in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinian people.
The Unified Packing for Cigarette Act has entered into force in Australia.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and images of disease-stricken body parts contrast on dull green boxes, which are the same for all cigarette stamps.
The first Australian law on uniform packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products has come into force in the world, replacing logos and colouring of different stamps with a box of dilapidated-liquid-coloured images of sick body parts and images of children whose health is affected by the smoking of their parents.
In addition to the various images and inscriptions that warn of the dangers of smoking, the only difference between packages introduced on this Saturday is the name of the stamps, which are printed in the same small font.
These are the most difficult conditions in the world for packaging tobacco.
The Australian Federal Government states that the aim of this measure is to prevent young people from smoking, depriving them of this dangerous fashion habit.
This decision was based on studies showing that people who had not started smoking before 26 years of age had never become smokers in 99 cases out of 100.
"It is evident that even when they are young, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging," explains the Minister of Health, Tanya Plybersek, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with children's idea of a princess.
Australia was one of the countries with the lowest smoking rate in the world, so that those changes would not affect the returns of transnational corporations much, but other countries were already considering such measures.
The tobacco industry has strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
The tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market in which cheap and accessible cigarettes are sold.
"This law will have serious consequences that are different from those which have been suggested by its initiators," said Scott McIntyre, a British American Tobacco agent in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply much more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, new laws contribute to business growth.
Sandra Ha of a small family company, Zico Import Pty Ltd, claims that the demand for cigarettes and silicon cabinets concealing unpleasant images on the package has grown rapidly (practicably from zero) since two months ago companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost their case in Australia's High Court, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about 6,000 pieces to the bulk industry and is waiting for a new batch.
It's a good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among the target population.
Following the passage of a series of laws in Australia that have made illegal television advertisements of cigarettes and their support for sporting events, as well as bans on the placing of cigarettes on the spot, tobacco advertisements have been moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has prohibited local companies and websites from posting advertisements online, but it cannot restrict foreign websites.
"If you sell tobacco and you have only this little loophole left, the idea of moving your product online would seem very tempting to you," explains Beki Freeman, a student of public health at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of salesmark reviews written on behalf of alleged common users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question is, is it really the work of a private citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he's spared his energy and time and made a video, or is it the advertising company that's behind it?
British American Tobacco, Australia, claims that the industry is now more engaged in adapting to new rules than advertising.
The tobacco industry had even undertaken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: those States were filing claims under the World Trade Organization, arguing that trade had been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that trade relations between all those countries and Australia were very small.
A decision by the World Trade Organization is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanya Plybersek, the Government had discussed with other countries the possibility of introducing similar packing laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first to introduce mandatory smoking warning photos.
This rule has now been adopted in over 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Great Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India are considering the possibility of tightening their laws.
Many smokers in Australia do not obey innovation.
These pictures don't bother me.
I just don't mind.
"Just grab a cigarette and hide a pack in your pocket," explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumour on a pack.
To be honest, the only thing that can make me quit is my little daughter.
James Yu, manager of the tobacco store, King of the Pack in central Sydney, claims that the same packaging has made it difficult to place the goods on the shelves.
"Before I had an hour to unload the new batch, and now it's four o'clock," he complains.
"The government had to take and completely ban cigarettes, we would have said, what to do, okay, it's over, shut the store," he said, throwing his hands up.
Missing in a world of electronic networks and constant connections isn't so bad.
On this thanksgiving day I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had mechanical problems and was replaced with another plane that we were waiting for.
So I had enough time to think about the nature of boredom.
I won't deceive you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and neither books nor magazines nor iPhone nor even duty-free shops will help.
Recently, however, more and more researchers and professionals in child development have been expressing themselves in favour of boredom.
They say that in certain situations it is not so bad for us and for our children to miss.
This forces the brain to distract itself from interesting related themes, which may contribute to creativity.
And since in today's world all of us are constantly in front of some screen, the advantages of boredom pass us by.
Maybe we should pursue boredom.
Yeah.
And at the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
I used to believe, like many, that boredom is an invention of relatively recent times, when people have had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at Calgary University of Canada, author of the book Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
"In fact, boredom can boast of a very ancient history," he says.
The walls of Pompeii have found Latin boredom inscriptions dated the first century.
However, the question of how we understand boredom remains open.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying research on this subject and asking a question to a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came up with the following definition: boredom is when people “have but cannot do what pleases them”.
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored man doesn't do anything he wants to do.
I don't want to do anything with apathy.
The main thing in the boredom is, he says, "disobedient attention and the resulting loss of mood and the feeling that time is taking slow."
The description of boredom may seem very depressive.
However, Professor Eastwood claims that despite the possible connection between these conditions, bored people see the causes of the problems in the world and the circumstances, while depressed people see the problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel like we're bored when it's really hard to focus on something.
In his study "Unoccupied Mind: Defining Boring From a Attention Perspective," published in September by the Journal of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to a previous experiment which had listened to a recording of a voice reading the magazine.
Some participants also heard loud sounds of a non-essential television program in the next room, others heard the same sounds on low volume, so they could hardly be addressed, and a third group listened only to recording a voice without a foreign sound track.
Those who heard a low volume TV said they were bored, more often -- they had difficulty getting focused, but they didn't know the reason and attributed it to the boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, interrupting attention can cause boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at Gwelph University, Ontario, and one of the authors of this study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, "for example, by looking into the flow of goods on the conveyor in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom."
It's believed that when people start to swing on a chair or draw carakul on a piece of paper, they do it for boredom, but now we know that, in fact, such actions just help not to relax physically.
"The study found that children who are not prevented from being bullied and rotating learn better and learn more information than children who are being asked to sit still," said Professor Fenske.
At some point we all get bored: in the delay of the flight (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting movie.
However, different people show different degrees of boredom.
In the 1980s, researchers developed a special “discipline scale” to measure such individual characteristics.
To determine an estimate on such a scale, questions and suggestions are used, such as "Much of what I have to do is uniformly and monotonously" or "I'm too interested, so there's not enough time for anything."
With such a survey, researchers have found that boys miss girls more frequently,” says Stephen Oddovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when there are a variety of external irritants.
In general, however, teenagers are often bored.
In 1991 Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, carried out an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven or eight times a day with a pager.
He received the following results: 32% of teenagers reported bored at school and during their homework, and 23% reported bored outside of school.
However, only 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
