UNASUR will end without the declaration of Lima
The VIth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without the declaration of the Lima Declaration, which was announced earlier and theoretically signed by the seven required participants.
Efe had repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VIrd ordinary meeting of heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources from the Office and the President's Administration had indicated on the front page that it would be handed over after closing, but had then confirmed that it would be published on the website of the Government of Peru at a certain time.
On questions about the text, they indicated that the contents had been submitted by the President of Peru, Oliant Umala, during brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information about the Summit was always restricted.
In the course of the day, only a video of the Presidential Assembly was broadcast in the press hall, with a message that said, "Close meeting, no sound."
A small amount of information which was circulating among reporters was provided by some UNASUR government spokespersons who attended the meeting, but not by Peru.
The only document distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discontent among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who requested more information.
Subsequently, the President's administration sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but this is about Umala's statement rather than the official document by which the summit ended.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South American and Arab Summit (ASPA), and the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was also not distributed, despite press insistence.
On the official ASPA website, you can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the authorities in Peru had endeavoured to ensure that broadcast systems were provided to all journalists, but had limited access to information as much as possible.
The meeting also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to adopt a verdict of the Court of The Hague, which settles a territorial dispute between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Oliant Umala, and Chile, Sebastian Pinera, have met at a regional meeting and have ratified that they will abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which begins on Monday in The Hague the hearing of the statements of both parties, in the context of the charge which Lima has put forward against Santiago.
"We will abide by and execute a decision that will explain the differences that we are currently representing in this international court," said Umala, next to her Chilean colleague.
"Chili was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of differences, pacts and international courts," he added, and greeted Umal with a shake of his hand against the flags of these two countries.
The confirmation by both Presidents that they were subject to the International Court of Justice took place immediately after Colombia protested this week against the Bogotá pact, according to which it recognized that it was subject to the verdicts of that international court following the decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered incorrect.
The meeting was held in the absence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseph; Venezuela, Ugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Christina Kirschner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR had been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former President, Fernando Lugo, had not participated in the meeting.
The host President, Olitta Umala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and for closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The Head of State had read the outcome document, in which he had reported that 16 agreements had been adopted and action lines had been approved for 31 projects among South American countries, and that the expected investment amounted to $17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries would take “important steps towards the purpose of South American citizenship for which we are extending the settlement agreement”.
He reported that action was being taken to improve “cooperation in the fight against citizens' uncertainty and organized transnational crime, action to increase access to drugs, low-cost Internet access in all parts of South America and to take into account the combined and effective risks of natural disasters”.
Since Europe is in crisis, “the economic union (Latin America) should not have a triumphant basis, but should serve to expand our productive base and foreshadow a better future for our cities,” Oomala added.
"We decided to grant privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that would improve South America's communications, especially in the village and border areas ... bringing our countries together and forming new economic schemes," the President of Peru said in a read.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were from Peru and were confined to transverse axes on its territory, from coast to Brazil, while two were intended to have a greater connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide any more details.
The outcome document also addressed the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in that country will serve to rejoin the Union of South American Nations," from which it is now excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of well-being and peace, to be united and to have good relations among its neighbours was another theme highlighted at the Summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said that, before taking part in the regional meeting, he hoped to meet with his colleague from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City, to conduct a respectful negotiation of the maritime dispute as a result of the verdict of an international court challenged by Bogotá.
"The next morning (saturday), perhaps meet President Daniel Ortega," said Santos.
"Let's renegotiate all these ways, they're not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua," he stressed.
